or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graney","meanings":["Irish (Galway, Cork, and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Raighne</b> ‘son of <i>Raighne</i>’, a pet form of <i>Raghnall</i>. It has sometimes been changed to   Grant  . See also   Rainey  .","Possibly an altered form of Swiss German <b>Gräni</b>, unexplained."]},{"name":"Grand","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i> ‘tall, large’, from Latin <i>grandis</i>. See also   Grant   1 and 4, compare   Degrand   and   Legrand  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived in a gravelly area, from Middle Low German <i>grand</i> ‘coarse gravel’.","German: nickname from a southern word of uncertain origin meaning ‘frustration, anger, ire’."]},{"name":"Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Domenic, Mario, Antonio, Santo, Orlando, Americo, Carmine, Gennaro, Luigi, Pasquale, Saverio, Alberico.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alicia, Ricardo, Jorge, Juan, Raul, Angel, Atilio.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: nickname for someone of large stature, in either a literal or figurative sense, from <i>grande</i> ‘tall, large’.","German: habitational name from Grande in Holstein or Grand in Bavaria."]},{"name":"General","meanings":["African American: from the English vocabulary word <i>general</i>, possibly adopted as a surname in honor of a certain general of the US army, most probably Ulysses S. Grant (see   Grant  , compare   President  ). Compare also 3 below.","German: nickname for a mercenary (employed in royal services).","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): nickname from Spanish <i>general</i> ‘general’ (military officer)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":113,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Grant was born about 1342, in Stevenstone, Devon, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth de Stevenstone."},"et":{"about 1342–":"umbes 1342–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1364–1384":"1364–1384","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1364":"1364","1342":"1342","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","about 1342":"umbes 1342","Stevensto